<p>Belgium reported multiple unmanned aerial vehicles over the Doel nuclear power plant this weekend; the operator Engie said the sightings did not affect plant operations. Belgian authorities are monitoring the situation and have accepted personnel and equipment offers from France, Germany and the United Kingdom to help protect sensitive sites. Belgian intelligence services suspect foreign involvement, and local reporting has pointed to Moscow as a plausible source, though no definitive public attribution has been made.</p><h3>Highlights:</h3><ul><li>Detection details: Engie said initial reports indicated three drones shortly before 10 p.m., growing to five, and the devices remained airborne for about an hour.</li><li>Airspace disruptions: Belgium has seen a string of incidents: Brussels and Liège airports faced interruptions last week and drones were spotted over military bases and the Port of Antwerp, stressing civil aviation and port-security monitoring.</li><li>International support: British Armed Forces chief Richard Knighton announced London will deploy anti-drone specialists to assist Belgium’s protection of airports and military sites, joining France and Germany’s offers of personnel and equipment.</li><li>Political fallout: Belgian defense minister Theo Francken framed the incidents as part of &#x27;hybrid threats&#x27; and has previously drawn international attention for remarks about Russia that Moscow has publicly condemned.</li></ul><blockquote>Initially we had detected three drones, but then we saw five drones. They were up in the air for about an hour - Hellen Smeets</blockquote><h3>Perspectives:</h3><ul><li>Engie (operator): Engie reported the drones over the Doel plant and said the sightings had no impact on plant operations, aiming to reassure the public about safety. (<a href='https://www.politico.eu/article/drones-spotted-belgium-nuclear-plant-doel-airspace-incursions/'>POLITICO Europe</a>)</li><li>Belgian interior ministry / Crisis Centre: Belgium&#x27;s national Crisis Center confirmed it was monitoring the incidents and, after a National Security Council meeting, officials said authorities had the situation &#x27;under control&#x27;. (<a href='https://www.politico.eu/article/drones-spotted-belgium-nuclear-plant-doel-airspace-incursions/'>POLITICO Europe</a>)</li><li>British Armed Forces: Chief of the British Armed Forces Richard Knighton said London would help Brussels counter drone incursions by sending specialists and equipment to protect airports and bases. (<a href='http://www.euronews.com/2025/11/09/suspicious-drone-activity-in-belgium-uk-will-send-special-team-to-support-brussels'>Euronews</a>)</li></ul><h3>Sources:</h3><ul><li><a href='https://www.politico.eu/article/drones-spotted-belgium-nuclear-plant-doel-airspace-incursions/'>Belgium flounders as 5 drones buzz nuclear power plant</a> - politico.eu</li><li><a href='http://www.euronews.com/2025/11/09/suspicious-drone-activity-in-belgium-uk-will-send-special-team-to-support-brussels'>UK deploys anti-drone specialists to Belgium after string of incursions</a> - euronews.com</li><li><a href='https://www.rt.com/news/627543-british-anti-drone-unit-belgium/'>British anti-drone unit deployed to Belgium – defense minister</a> - rt.com</li><li><a href='https://www.reddit.com/r/worldnews/comments/1osw6w7/three_drones_were_detected_above_belgiums_doel/'>Three drones were detected above Belgium&#x27;s Doel nuclear power plant on Sunday evening</a> - reddit.com</li><li><a href='https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/articles/c3dn2ep584ko'>The United Kingdom announces it is deploying its military to Belgium to help protect its airports amid a series of drone incursions over the country&#x27;s airspace.</a> - bbc.co.uk</li></ul>